            <div class="ins_notes">
                <span class="note" id="note-1"><a href="#ref-1">[1]</a> This is not a self-standing decree, but its text is incorporated in the naval inventories for 325/4.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-2"><a href="#ref-2">[2]</a> Miltiades of Lakiadai (<a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/1629"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1629</a>, 18-19), descendant of the Miltiades who had led the Athenian colonising expedition to the Thracian Chersonese in the sixth century (Hdt. 6.36). His appointment reflects a historical consciousness, and an aspiration to reconnect with its imperial past, that is characteristic of Athens at this period. There is no other evidence for the colony founded under this decree.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-3"><a href="#ref-3">[3]</a> That the Etruscans posed a threat to Athenian commerce in the Adriatic at this period is confirmed by lost speeches of Hypereides, "On protection against the Etruscans", and Deinarchos, "Etruscan" speech. See also <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/460"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 4, 460</a>; <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII31/336"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 1, 336</a>.</span>
            </div>
            

